# murmer-rs simulation architecture: the seams murmer must own

> **Audience:** murmer-rs maintainers/agent, and the appdata/datastorekit team.
> **Status:** authoritative design target. Companion to
> `2026-06-21-murmer-deterministic-runtime-proposal.md` (the P0 ask).
> **Scope:** murmer's lane only. appdata owns disk, the SQLite VFS, HEAD fence
> enforcement, and the oracles; that content lives in appdata's architecture doc.

## TL;DR

The goal is FoundationDB-grade deterministic simulation testing (DST) for the whole
appdata-on-murmer stack: one bit-deterministic simulation of the entire cluster, N
nodes, real actors, real SQLite, bit-reproducible from a seed, faulted everywhere,
checked end-to-end. No black box, no "tested a subset and hope," no `local()` vs
`clustered()` validity gap.

murmer's job in that goal is to provide the **seams for the pillars it owns** and the
**discipline to have no escape hatches**. Concretely, five things:

1. A **Runtime seam** (spawn, time, rng, blocking-exec-context) with a `TokioRuntime`
   default and `System::with_runtime(...)` injection.
2. A **determinism contract + CI gate** that closes the leaks the seam is blind to
   (biased `select!`, deterministic iteration, no stray nondeterminism tokens).
3. A **Net/transport seam** so the cluster runs over a deterministic in-memory bus in
   sim, with partition/latency/reorder/loss/node-death injection.
4. A **fence**: a durably-monotonic, consensus-grade ownership token for singletons.
5. **Context-gates-everything** plus a shared **`buggify!()`** hook.

The organizing principle, the one that makes the whole stack reachable: a component is
simulatable exactly when it externalizes its IO, time, and randomness through a seam.
murmer's job is to *be* that seam for its own pillars, and to prefer dependencies that
already are one.

## Scope: who owns which pillar

Determinism decomposes into six pillars. murmer owns roughly four and a half; disk is
appdata's. Do not double-count disk as a murmer deliverable.

| Pillar | Owner | Made deterministic by |
|---|---|---|
| scheduling / spawn | **murmer** | Runtime seam |
| clock | **murmer** | Runtime seam |
| rng | **murmer** | Runtime seam (`rng()`) + the `rand::` decision sites |
| iteration order | **murmer** (its maps) + appdata (its maps) | deterministic-hasher / `BTreeMap` discipline |
| network | **murmer** | Net seam → in-memory deterministic bus |
| disk | **appdata** | `pio` / `SimFileSystem` fault-fs (not murmer's) |
| coordination / fence | **murmer** (token) + **appdata** (HEAD enforcement) | monotonic token + resource-side CAS |

## The north star

One simulation that runs the entire service, single node up to a full multi-node
cluster, deterministically from a seed, under pervasive fault injection, checked by an
end-to-end integrity oracle. Same binary; you swap the runtime. This mirrors FDB's
`INetwork`/`Sim2`: one swappable substrate under the whole actor framework, real
(`Net2`) versus simulated (`Sim2`).

murmer is appdata's Flow. The seams below are murmer's `INetwork`.

---

## 1. The Runtime seam

One swappable abstraction that all murmer concurrency routes through. `TokioRuntime` is
the default, so production is byte-for-byte unchanged. Actors reach it only through
`Context`; they never touch `tokio::`, `std::time`, `rand`, or raw sockets directly.

```rust
/// The single swappable runtime seam. Default = TokioRuntime (today's behavior).
pub trait Runtime: Send + Sync + 'static {
    // --- spawn ---
    /// Replaces every internal tokio::spawn.
    fn spawn(&self, fut: BoxFuture<'static, ()>) -> TaskHandle;

    // --- time ---
    fn now_monotonic(&self) -> Instant;
    fn now_wall(&self) -> SystemTime;
    fn sleep(&self, dur: Duration) -> BoxFuture<'static, ()>;
    fn interval(&self, period: Duration) -> Box<dyn IntervalStream>;
    // timeout derivable from sleep + a biased select.

    // --- rng ---
    /// Seeded in sim; OS entropy in prod. Covers the rand:: decision sites.
    fn rng(&self) -> Box<dyn RngCore + Send>;

    // --- blocking execution context (the SQLite enabler) ---
    /// Run a synchronous unit of work. Prod: offload to a dedicated thread so real
    /// NFS/SQLite IO never blocks the actor pool. Sim: run inline under the
    /// deterministic scheduler. NOT a passthrough to tokio::spawn_blocking.
    fn run_blocking(&self, work: Box<dyn FnOnce() + Send>) -> BoxFuture<'static, ()>;
}

pub struct TokioRuntime; // default; #[inline] passthrough to tokio.

impl System {
    pub fn with_runtime(runtime: Arc<dyn Runtime>) -> Self; // sim path
    // existing constructors default to Arc::new(TokioRuntime)
}
```

### Why `run_blocking` is not `spawn_blocking`

This is the single piece appdata needs from murmer to make the SQLite half
deterministic, and it is the subtlest method on the trait.

`tokio::spawn_blocking` hands work to an uncontrolled thread pool the sim scheduler
cannot see, which breaks the quiescence contract (the scheduler can no longer tell when
all tasks are parked, so it cannot safely advance virtual time). So `run_blocking` must
be a first-class seam:

- **Prod:** a dedicated execution context (the connection-thread model) does real
  NFS/SQLite IO off the actor pool.
- **Sim:** the work runs **inline on the deterministic thread as one atomic step**.

The inline-atomic collapse is what makes the SQLite story tractable, and it holds
*because* of single-connection-per-container: the VFS callbacks return synchronously
from in-memory structures, so a SQLite transaction never yields mid-flight and never
interleaves with another actor. **This invariant is a shared constraint.** If
single-connection-per-container ever softens, SQLite can wait on a lock held by another
connection, "atomic inline" breaks, and the sim needs a deterministic in-memory lock
model plus virtual-time busy-waits. Protect the invariant.

### The determinism root

The Runtime seam is not just murmer's pillar. The SQLite VFS routes `xCurrentTime` to
*the* virtual clock and `xRandomness` to *the* seeded rng, and those are this trait's
`now_*` and `rng()`. SQLite's determinism draws from murmer's seam. The Runtime is the
**root of the determinism tree**; SQLite's VFS is a leaf that pulls from it. One stray
`Instant::now()` inside murmer desynchronizes SQLite's clock from everything else's. So
the no-escape-hatch gate (item 2) protects the seed-source the whole stack feeds from,
not just murmer's own correctness.

