## 4. The fence: a consensus-grade, durably-monotonic ownership token

This is murmer's half of the split-brain corruption fix. appdata enforces it at the
HEAD. Neither half is sufficient alone.

### The token (murmer mints it)

- A **durably-monotonic fencing token** tied to singleton ownership. The real defect
  today is that `GenerationSource` (`app/singleton.rs`) is in-memory and resets on
  restart, so it is **not monotonic across failover**. The fix is monotonicity that
  survives ownership changes, durably. That alone, paired with resource-side
  enforcement, closes the corruption hole (Kleppmann fencing tokens), even before
  election quality is perfect.

### The backing (consensus-grade, adopt-not-build)

- Replace `OldestNode` (`app/election.rs`), which is a heuristic, with genuinely
  single-owner ownership. **Adopt** a proven consensus (openraft) or an external
  coordinator as the monotonic source. Do **not** hand-roll Paxos.
- The justification is robustness, not cost: a home-grown consensus tangled into tokio
  would be both unproven and unsimulatable. openraft externalizes its network and
  storage through `RaftNetwork`/`RaftStorage`, so it runs over the sim bus and sim
  storage by design. The property that makes it robust is the same one that makes it
  testable.
- This half is validated **under the Net seam**: you can only torture election quality
  with partition injection, so consensus-grade ownership comes after item 3.

### The API contract (document the boundary loudly)

- murmer mints the token. The resource (appdata's HEAD) must CAS-enforce it. murmer
  **cannot** fence a resource it does not own (an NFS file, in appdata's case), so the
  singleton API must not imply that holding ownership makes writes safe on its own.
- The explicit decision murmer commits to: **the singleton is a fenced
  exclusive-ownership primitive (consensus-backed token), not best-effort placement.**
  Name and document it as such, or rename it so users are not misled.

